Building
--------

The challenge implementation was developed in Windows 10 OS with:

- Java JDK v11.0.9.101
- Eclipse v4.18 and Buildship plugin v3.1.4
- Gradle v7.1

Other IDEs and versions may work but have been not tested so far.

Once the code is unpacked you can import the project in Eclipse as a Gradle
project, refresh Gradle project (right-click on project, Gradle option), and
finally open the Gradle Tasks view and launch the jar task under build group.

If everything goes well a file named "nrcc-1.0.jar" will be built into
project's build/libs/ directory. This jar requires the Apache Commons CLI
jar v1.4 in the classpath. 

Building a runnable jar that doesn't require additional classpath is possible
from the command line, change into project top directory and type:

> gradle serverJar

Upon success a file name "nrcc-1.0-all.jar" will be built into project's
build/libs/ directory.

It's also possible to build a runnable test client with:

> gradle clientJar

This will create a "nrcc-1.0-client.jar" in the same directory.

Running
-------

A JVM v1.8 or greater is needed to run the application. For the server the
following command can be used: 

> path/to/java -jar path/to/nrcc-1.0-all.jar [options]

Of course you don't need to specify the path to java if the JVM bin directory
is already included on your PATH, neither the path to the jar file if you are
already in the build/libs/ directory.

You can specify an option (-d) which is the directory where the numbers
log will be written upon termination. If this parameter is not given the
current directory will be used to write the log. Try -h option for details.

The client can run the same way, just using the client jar:

> path/to/java -jar path/to/nrcc-1.0-client.jar [options]

Unless a different server is specified with -s option, client will connect to
the local host by default. Try -h option for details on all command line
arguments of the client.
